snippet.textDisplay:
I just want to make two points here real quick, not that it will make a difference, but whatever.

Point #1. The penny principle: If you deposit a penny in a jar on day one, then double it every day for 30 days, in one month you will have over 11 million dollars. This is called exponential growth. The Coronavirus could also spread exponentially if we do not shut everything down until we get it under control.

Point #2: Since we the people have to bail out the banks every time they get in trouble (usually by their own doing), then I think it is only fair that during this shutdown, the banks cannot collect a nickel from any of their loans. This means they can collect no house payments, car payments, or payments of any kind from the American people during the shutdown. This is only fair, and it's the right thing to do. Anything less us unacceptable. The majority of the population have been struggling just to survive. Now you throw this at them and millions will become unemployed, homeless and destitute. The ONLY acceptable course of action is to cease and desist any and all payments. This means that the power company, gas company, cell phone service companies, etc. cannot collect or even require payments, charge late fees, or shut off your service.

If the government is placing restrictions on the people, then they MUST also place restrictions on the banks and service companies which we depend on for our survival. Anything less would be a forced extinction of our way of life, and will destroy homes, families, careers and yes, even lives. SOMETHING must be done to protect the American people. The stimulus is a start, but that is not the answer. Corporations will benefit more than individuals, they always do. The answer is to force the banks to eliminate the burden on the people who earn less than $100k per year. If you earn more than that, sorry, you've had plenty of opportunities, but most Americans have had NO opportunities, and now they are being forced out of their jobs, homes and possibly out of existence all together. A shutdown is necessary, I agree, but we must not allow it do destroy our economy and our lives. We must also shut down the burdens placed on the people. It is only right, only fair, and the ONLY acceptable solution.

snippet.textDisplay: The observations of what Mr. Gates called exemplars (China and S. Korea) don't apply to the US at this time because there has not been a uniform or adequate shutdown across the US. Many locations are not even sheltering in place and in Austin, Texas (for example) there are not enough test kits to even test the number of people with symptoms (this is not an atypical situation). There is an "ordered" shelter in place, but with spotty enforcement and inadequate test kits, health officials are warning of accelerated contagion. In the larger population centers in the US where adequate shutdown and shelter-in-place has not happened, the contagion, hospitalizations and deaths will burgeon until such areas retrench with adequate measures. States where mandatory shutdowns were implemented early are experiencing slow and or slowing levels of contagion but with interstate travel they are still at risk of new outbreaks and consequently need to continue shutdown.  It is impossible to measure how big the disaster in the US will become until the Administration and Congress roll out an adequate plan to turn the tide on contagion. Not sure if there could have been a poorer national response contrary to what we're hearing from the White House.
